description: Demolition of 156 existing residential units and other associated structures; the retention of 30 existing residential units and the construction of 287 new residential units in six apartment buildings between four and eight storeys high and two and three storey houses comprising 46 one-bedroom, 71 two-bedroom and 10 three-bedroom flats and 39 two-bedroom, 89 three-bedroom, 27 four-bedroom and five five-bedroom houses; 70sq.m floor space in retail use (A1 Use Class) and 280sq.m floor space in community use (D1 Use Class); refuse and recycling facilities; bicycle storage facilities; 235 car parking spaces; landscaping including new public open space and children's play space, associated public realm and highways works. This application constitutes a Departure from the Local Plan.
decision_conditions: The development permitted shall be begun before the expiration of three years from the date of this permission.  Reason: In order to comply with the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended). | The development hereby approved shall be carried out in accordance with the following approved plans and documents:   (390_PL_Ph1_): 001A, 002 B, 020 B, 021 B, 022 B, 023 B, 024 B, 025 B, 026 B, 027 A, 028 B, 029 A, 030 B, 031 B, 032 A, 033 A, 034 B, 035 B, 036 B, 037 B, 038 A, 039 A, 040 B, 041 B, 042 B, 043 B, 044 A, 045 B, 046 C, 100 A, 101 B, 102 B, 103 C, 104 C, 105 B, 153 B, 154 A, 200 A, 201 B, 202 B, 203 A, 204 B, 205 B, 206 A, 207 B, 208 A, 209 A, 210 B, 211 A, 212 A; (IA-350-LP) : P01 A, P02 A, P03 A, P04 A, P05 A, P06 A, P07 A, P08 A; IA-350-LS-P01 A; AIA30-4-13-002-A-proposals-A1; AIA30-4-13-003-A-work-A1; AIA30-4-13-002-B-shade-A1; AIA30-4-13-003-B-protect-dem-A1; AIA30-4-13-003-C-protect-con-A1;   Phase 1 Design & Access Statement (dated July 2013 and updated by 'Addendum for Planning October 2013', prepared by PTEa and Ireland Albrecht Landscape Architects); Planning & Regeneration Statement (Project ref: 21744/A5/Planning Statement Issue 03, dated June 2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore Ltd); Affordable Housing Statement (Ref: 21744/A5, July 2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore Ltd); Ecological Scoping Survey (dated December, 2012 and prepared by Furesfen), Habitat and Breeding Bird Survey Report (dated May 2013 and prepared by Furesfen), Bat Survey Report (and addendum including fourth bat survey on 23/07/2013 and prepared by Furesfen); Arboricultural Implications Assessment and Arboricultural Method Statement (Ref: AIA30-4-13, 05/06/2013, prepared by M.Clews on behalf of Arborhelp) and BS5837 Survey & Initial Work Schedule for Trees Surveyed at Havelock Estate (prepared by M. Clews on behalf of Arborhelp); Health Impact Assessment (Project ref: 21744/A5/VL/HIA, June 2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore Ltd); Socio Economics Report (Project ref: 21744/A5, dated July 2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore LLP); Heritage Statement (ref: LH/14931, July 2013, prepared by CgMs Ltd); Wind Environment Assessment (Issue 2, Project ref: 00037231-001, dated 28/06/2013, prepared by ); Air Quality Assessment (Ref: 27760/005 Issue 1, 03/07/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates LLP); Noise Assessment (Ref: 27760-006/Issue 1, 03/07/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates LLP); Geotechnical and geoenvironmental interpretive report (Ref: CG/08135, February 2013, prepared by Card Geotechnicals Limited); Environmental Considerations (Ref: 21744/A5 Issue 03, July 2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore LLP); Lighting Impact Appraisal Assessment (Ref: 27760/Issue 1, 03/07/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates LLP); Sunlight, Daylight and Overshadowing Assessment (ref: 32992/IM/nms, dated 08/07/2013, prepared by Malcolm Hollis LLP) and updated assessment by Letter (ref: 32992/IM/SK, dated 18/10/2013, prepared by Malcolm Hollis LLP); Addendum to Transport Assessment (including vehicle tracking diagrams) (ref: 27760-001 Doc ref: 01, dated 16/10/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates), Transport Technical Note (ref: 27760-001, dated 07/10/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates); Construction Management Plan (no ref & un-dated, prepared by Leadbitter Group); Flood Risk Assessment (Project Ref: 27760/Issue 1, May 2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates); Sustainability Report including updated Appendix 5 (Ref: EST6090 Issue 1, 10/07/2013, prepared by Bespoke Builder Services Ltd), Addednum II Sustainability Report (Ref: EST-6090/add II Issue 1, October 2013, prepared by Bespoke Builder Services Ltd); Statement of Community Involvement (Prepared by Catalyst Housing Ltd); Utilities & Foul Drainage Assessment (Ref: 27760/001 Issue 1, 03/07/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates LLP).  Reason: For the avoidance of doubt and in the interests of proper planning. | Prior to the demolition of buildings, removal of vegetation and/ or the felling of trees within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), an Ecological Survey of the gardens and buildings within the relevant part of the development site not surveyed as part of the approved Bat Survey Report (prepared by Furesfen and updated July 2013) and Phase 1 Habitat & Breeding Bird Survey Report (prepared by Furesfen) shall be carried out and submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The additional Ecological Survey shall include the following information:  A) The results of a detailed internal and external inspection of all buildings within the site with potential to support priority species, nesting birds, bat roosts and other noted species; B) The results of a detailed inspection of the trees and other vegetation identified as having potential to support priority species, nesting birds, bat roosts and other noted species; C) If necessary, as evidenced through the findings of sub-points (A) and (B), the results of evening emergence survey for all buildings assessed as having medium to high potential to support roosting bats; and D) Details of measures that have or will be incorporated into the scheme to avoid contravention of The Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended) and The Conservation of Habitats and Species Regulations 2010   The measures identified under sub-point (D) shall be implemented in accordance with the recommendations as approved.  The surveys shall be carried out in accordance with the Bat Conservation Trust Survey Guidelines and other guidance as relevant.   Reason: To ensure that protected species are appropriately safeguarded, in accordance with the relevant National legislation, including The Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended) and The Conservation of Habitats and Species Regulations 2010; the NPPF and policies 5.3 and 7.19 of the London Plan 2015 and 1.1(e) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012. | Prior to the commencement of development within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), a site construction logistics plan shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  The submission shall include the following:  A) A summary of the results of the Ecological Survey and the measures to be put in place to secure the necessary mitigation measures to protect priority species, priority habitats, nesting birds, bat roosts and other noted species during the clearance of vegetation, felling of trees and demolition and construction works, including a commitment to employ a suitably qualified ecologist to oversee any works affecting priority habitats, priority species and other noted species; B) The number of on-site construction workers and details of the transport options and parking facilities for them; C) anticipated route, anticipated number, frequency and size of construction vehicles entering/exiting the site per day, and capping the maximum number of lorry movements to 30 trips per day; D) evidence that the use of the Grand Union Canal has been considered for transporting the demolition waste and other measures to reduce the impact of lorries on the local road network;  E) that appropriate measures are put in place to facilitate the operation of the E5 bus route and associated bus stops during construction works; F) that arrangements will be put in place to ensure the occupiers of Maypole Dock will be able to receive deliveries of propane gas by large vehicles; G) delivery times and booking system (which is to be staggered to avoid morning and afternoon school-run peak periods); H) route and location of site access for construction traffic and associated signage; I) management of consolidated or re-timed trips; J) Details of noise/vibration and dust mitigation measures and monitoring arrangements for noise, vibration and dust by suitably qualified noise and air quality specialists.  Noise/vibration and dust mitigation measures must accord with the Mayor's 'Best Practice Guidance: The control of dust and emissions from construction and demolition ' (2006) and BS 5228 Parts 1 & 2;  K) details of site security and the erection and maintenance of security hoarding including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing, where appropriate; L) secure, off-street loading and drop-off facilities; M) vehicle manoeuvring and turning, including swept path diagrams to demonstrate how construction vehicles will access the site and be able to turn into and emerge from the site in forward gear and including details of any temporary vehicle access points; N) details as to the location(s) for storage of building materials and construction debris and contractors offices; O) procedures for on-site contractors to deal with complaints from members of the public; P) measures to consult cyclists, disabled people and the local schools with regard  to delivery times and necessary diversions; Q) details of all pedestrian and cyclist diversions; R) a commitment to be part of Considerate Constructors Scheme; and S) confirmation of use of TfL's Freight Operator Recognition Scheme (FORS) or similar  Prior to the commencement of any site work, all sensitive properties surrounding the site shall be notified in writing of the nature and duration of the works to be undertaken, and the name and address of a responsible person to whom enquiries / complaints should be directed. These details shall also be displayed at regular intervals around the site construction compound.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved.  Any areas to be used for the storage of building materials or other site activities outside of the relevant phase of the development shall be returned to the original condition immediately following the practical completion of the development.  Reason:  To ensure appropriate mitigation measures to protect the amenity of local residents and ensure adequate highway and site safety; and also to ensure that protected species are appropriately safeguarded,  in accordance with policies 5.3, 5.18, 6.3, 7.14, 7.15 and 7.19 of the London Plan 2015; 1.1(e), 1.1(f) and 1.1(j) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; Ealing's SPG 10: Noise and Vibration; the National Planning Policy Framework (2012); The control of dust and emissions during construction and demolition (July 2014); BS 5228-1:2009 - Code of practice for noise & vibration control on construction & open sites-Part 1: Noise; The Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended) and The Conservation of Habitats and Species Regulations 2010. | Prior to the commencement of development within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), a Site Waste Management Plan shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The Site Waste Management Plan shall demonstrate how the procurement of materials for the development would promote sustainability, including by use of low impact, sustainably sourced, reused and recycled materials, including reuse of demolition waste, use of local suppliers and by reference to the BRE's Green Guide Specification.   The development shall be carried out in accordance with the particulars so approved.  Reason:  To ensure sustainable procurement of materials which minimises the negative environmental impacts of construction in accordance with policies 5.3 and 5.18 of the London Plan 2015, policies 1.1 (k) and 1.2 (f) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy LV5.2 of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | No development shall commence (including initial site clearance) within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant) until the tree protection measures detailed within the approved 'Arboricultural Implications Assessment / Arboricultural Method Statement for the Havelock Estate regeneration project Phase 1' (ref: AIA30-4-13, prepared by M. Clews of Aborhelp) have been put in place.  All tree protection methods detailed in the approved Arboricultural Method Statement shall not be moved or removed, temporarily or otherwise, until all works including external works have been completed and all equipment, machinery and surplus materials have been removed from the  site, unless the prior approval of the Local Planning Authority has first been sought and obtained.  The retention and adequate protection of all trees identified should be in accordance with the approved drawings IA-350-TP-P02 A (amended drawings received 18.10.2013).  Reason:  To safeguard the future of trees and shrubs in the interests of the visual amenities and the biodiversity value of the area and the setting and character of the proposed development in accordance with policies: 7.19 and 7.21 of the London Plan 2015; policy 1.1(i) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policy LV5.10 of Ealing's Development Management DPD; and SPG 9: Trees and Development Guidelines. | No development shall commence (including initial site clearance) within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant) until a suitable programme of monitoring of all approved tree protection measures has been submitted and approved by the Local Planning Authority.  The monitoring programme shall include the following:  A) Confirmation of who shall be the lead Arboriculturist for the development; B) Confirmation of the Site Manager, key personnel, their key responsibilities and contact details; C) Details of induction procedures for all personnel in relation to Arboricultural matters; D) A detailed timetable of events concerning the approved tree protection plans, including; initial implementation of the protective measures, the final removal of the protective measures and any incursion/alterations to accommodate site specific construction/demolition procedures as approved in the Arboricultural Method Statement and the level of supervision required; E) Procedures for dealing with variations or non-approved incursions into the construction exclusion zones as detailed in the approved Arboricultural Method Statement; F) Agreements of when site monitoring will take place with the local Tree Officer either by site meetings or by some other pre-arranged agreement; G) Post development assessment of the retained and planted trees and any necessary remedial action.  The programme of Arboricultural monitoring shall be undertaken in full compliance with the approved details.  No variation of the approved monitoring programme shall take place without the prior written agreement of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason: In order to safeguard trees and other vegetation considered to be worthy of retention in the interests of visual amenity for the area in accordance with policies: 7.21 of the London Plan 2015; policy 1.1(i) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policy LV5.10 of Ealing's Development Management DPD; and SPG 9: Trees and Development Guidelines. | Prior to the commencement of development (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works) within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), details in line with the criteria specified in Ealing's adopted Supplementary Planning Guidance 10 (Noise and Vibration) shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority, including, as appropriate, the noise exposure category and the BS4142 rating noise. The details shall also include the building envelope noise mitigation measures with windows closed and other means of ventilation provided and screening for external amenity areas where necessary.    The details shall also address the sound mitigation measures provided between the ceiling and floor of the non-residential and residential units.  The details as approved shall be implemented prior to the first occupation of any residential units in the relevant Phase.  Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of residential amenity is provided for future occupiers, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan 2015; policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD; and SPG10: Noise and Vibration. | Prior to the commencement of development (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works) within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), an air quality assessment report written in accordance with the relevant current guidance for the existing site and proposed development shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The report should have regard to the air quality predication and monitoring results from the Stage Four of the Authority's Review and Assessment, the London Air Quality Network and London Atmospheric Emissions Inventory. The report shall also include a scheme for air pollution mitigation measures to be incorporated into the development based on the findings of the air quality assessment.   The approved air quality mitigation measures shall be incorporated into the development prior to first occupation or use of the development.  Reason: The Air Quality Stage 4 Review and Assessment for the London Borough of Ealing has highlighted that this area currently experiences or is likely to experience exceedences of Government set air quality standards and air quality mitigation is required. It is necessary that future occupiers are not exposed to poor air quality that could have a negative impact on health and as such, mitigation would be necessary in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(e) and 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012 and policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Prior to the commencement of development (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works) within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), details shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority for the installation in each dwelling of an Ultra-Low NOx boiler with maximum NOx Emissions of under 40 mg/kWh.   The approved boilers shall be incorporated into the development prior to first occupation or use of the development.  Reason: To minimise the impact of building emissions on local air quality, in the interests of health, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(e) and 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012, and policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Prior to the commencement of development (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works) within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), a soil contamination investigation and risk assessment shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. This contamination investigation and risk assessment should include:   a) a survey of the extent, scale and nature of contamination;  b) an assessment of the potential risks to:- human health, property (existing or proposed) including buildings, crops, pets, woodland and service lines and pipes, adjoining land, groundwaters and surface waters, ecological systems;  c) A detailed soil contamination remediation scheme;   The soil contamination investigation must be conducted in accordance with DEFRA and the Environment Agency's 'Model Procedures for the Management of Land Contamination, CLR 11'.   The soil contamination remediation scheme must include all works to be undertaken, proposed contamination remediation objectives and contamination remediation criteria, timetable of works and site management procedures. The scheme must ensure that the site will not qualify as contaminated land under Part 2A of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 in relation to the intended use of the land after remediation.  Reason: To protect the health and living conditions of residents of the new development in accordance policy 1.1(e) of the Ealing Development (or Core) Strategy (2012); policy 5.21 of the London Plan 2015; policies LV5.21 and 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD; the National Planning Policy Framework (2012), and  DEFRA and the Environment Agency's 'Model Procedures for the Management of Land Contamination, CLR 11'. | The approved soil contamination remediation scheme must be carried out in accordance with the approved details. The Local Planning Authority must be given two weeks written notification of commencement of the remediation scheme works.   Following completion of measures identified in the approved remediation scheme, a verification report that demonstrates the effectiveness of the remediation carried out must be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for information.   The verification report submitted shall be in accordance with the Environment Agency guidance 'Verification of Remediation of Land Contamination', Report: SC030114/R1'.  Reason: To protect the health and living conditions of residents in the area in accordance policy 1.1(e) of the Ealing Development (or Core) Strategy (2012), policy 5.21 of the London Plan 2015; policy LV5.21 and 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD; the National Planning Policy Framework (2012), and  DEFRA and the Environment Agency's 'Model Procedures for the Management of Land Contamination, CLR 11'. | The scheme for surface water management and foul water solutions shall be provided in accordance with the recommendations contained within the approved Flood Risk Assessment (ref: 27760 Issue 1, prepared by Peter Brett Associates), drawings 27760-C-FRA-01 and 27760-C-FRA-02, and Utilities & Foul Drainage Assessment (ref: 27760/001, prepared by Peter Brett Associates).  Reason:  To minimise the risk of flooding, to improve and protect water quality, improve habitat and amenity and in the interests of the drainage network in accordance with policies 5.12, 5.13 and 5.14 of the London Plan 2015, policy 1.2(m) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy LV5.12 of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Details and samples of all facing materials shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any work commencing on the superstructure of the relevant Phase (1A and / or 1B). The samples and details shall include:  a) brickwork (including brick panels and mortar courses); b) render (including details of colour and texture); c) cladding materials, including roof finishes; d) all window treatments (including sections and reveals) and details of obscure glazing to a minimum height of 1500mm above finished floor level of the windows within the rear elevation of the community centre; e) building entrance details and material samples; f) balcony structures and balustrading treatment (including sections);  g) privacy screen treatment;  h) sub-station, refuse and bicycle store entrance doors and ventilation louvres;  i) details of the design of the shopfront;  j) any other materials to be used.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved.   Reason:  In the interest of securing sustainable development and to ensure that the resulting appearance of the development is of a high standard in accordance with policies: 7.4 and 7.6 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(h), 1.1(k), 1.2(f), 1.2(h) and 2.9  of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policies LV7.4 and 7B of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Notwithstanding the detailed landscaping and public realm proposals illustrated on approved drawings ref: IA-350-SK (dated 14.10.13), IA-350-LGA-P02A, IA-350-LP-P01A, IA-350-LP-P02A, IA-350-LP-P03A, IA-350-LP-P04A and the Biodiversity Strategy, Tree Strategy and Play Strategy (prepared by Ireland Albrecht, dated 18.10.2013), amended and / or further details shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority within six (6) months of the commencement of the development of the following matters:  a) Full details of the children and teen play areas, including safety surfacing and equipment; b) Soft landscaping: including grass and turf areas, hedges, shrub and herbaceous areas, and tree strategy including species type and size at planting. Tree species should omit the use of Quercus robur and should include a palette of different species of trees in order to avoid streets and long sections of landscaping that are planted in monocultures; c) Hard landscaping: including ground surfaces, kerbs, edges, ridge and flexible paving, seating or other public realm furniture, steps, and any synthetic surfaces; d) Enclosures and boundary treatments, including types, dimensions and finishes of walls, fences, screen walls, barriers, bollards, rails, retaining walls and hedges; e) A statement detailing how the landscaping proposals contribute to mitigation measures for nesting birds, the enablement of species to migrate such as hedgehogs and other small mammals through gaps in fencing and ecological enhancements detailed within the approved Biodiversity Strategy and Ecological Surveys; f) Work phasing plan.  Any trees or shrubs that die within five years of planting shall be replaced with the same species of the same size or an approved alternative and to the satisfaction of the Local Planning Authority during the next planting season.  The development shall thereafter be carried out in accordance with the approved plans and details. Boundary treatments shall be fully provided before the first occupation of the area of development which it forms part.  Reason: In order that the Local Planning Authority could be satisfied with the design of the public space and because the provision of the public open space and the associated children's play space is required in order to provide mitigation for the loss of public open space within the site as a result of the proposals to develop on existing areas of designated public open space and in order to ensure that the resulting development is provided with an acceptable scheme of replacement open space, in accordance with the policy requirements set out at paragraph 74 of the NPPF; policies 7.18, 7.19 and 7.21 of the London Plan 2015;  policies 1.1(e), 1.1(i), 1.2(d), 5.4 and 5.5 of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy LV2.18 and 7D of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Prior to the commencement of superstructure works within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), full details of all public street tree pits including their locations, dimensions and depths in relation to ground levels, underground services, refuse stores serving the apartment buildings, car-parking bays and hard landscaping shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.   New tree planting shall accord, where feasible following further detailed investigative surveys, with the mitigation strategy contained within the approved Design and Access Statement (specifically the 'Tree Strategy', prepared by Ireland Albrecht, revised dated 18.10.13). The species and size of trees shall be agreed under condition 15.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved.  Reason:  To secure the appropriate provision and development of the proposed street-trees and to ensure that the life of the trees would not be unduly constrained in accordance with policies 5.10, 7.4, 7.5 and 7.21 of the London Plan 2015; policy 1.1(i) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and SPG 9: Trees and Development Guidelines. | The biodiversity roofs shall be laid out in accordance with the approved 'Proposed Biodiversity Strategy' contained within the Design and Access Statement (prepared by Ireland Albrecht, addendum dated 18.10.2013) and shall comprise of the following:  A) Be biodiversity based with extensive substrate base (depth 80-150mm);  B) Have sufficient depth of soil or growing medium for the relevant planting, including the re-use of any demolition material where feasible; C) Be planted / seeded with a mix of species within the first planting season following the practical completion of the building works. The seed mix shall be focused on wildflower planting and shall contain no more than 25% sedum; D) Have relevant efficient and effective drainage and irrigation to sustain the vegetation.  The biodiversity roofs shall not be used as an amenity or sitting out area and shall only be accessed in the case of essential maintenance or repair.  Reason:  To ensure the development provides the maximum possible provision towards the creation of habitats and valuable areas for biodiversity in accordance with policies 5.3, 5.10, 5.11, 5.12 and 7.19 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(j), 1.1(k) and 1.2(m) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policies LV5.10, LV5.11 and LV5.12 of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | None of the dwellings shall be occupied within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant) until footways from the public highway to the entrance of the property have been provided in accordance with the approved layout, and completed and surfaced in accordance with the approved hardsurfacing details and relevant work-phasing plan.   The details of footways shall be agreed under the provisions of condition 15 of this permission.   Reason:  To ensure safe and adequate access is provided to the building in the interest of the residents and visitors to the development in accordance with policies 6.10, 7.2, 7.3, 7.4 and 7.5 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(f) and 1.1(g) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy 7B of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | The car parking spaces illustrated on the approved drawings shall be marked out and completed prior to first occupation of any of the residential dwellings within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant), and these spaces together with the associated access roads and manoeuvring areas shall be kept continuously available for car and motorcycle parking and shall not be used for any other purpose.  Reason: To ensure adequate car parking is provided and retained in conjunction with the development in the interests of the general amenities of the locality and the free flow of traffic and conditions of pedestrian and general highway safety on the neighbouring highways in accordance with policies 6.13, 7.2, 7.3, 7.4 and 7.5 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(f) and 1.1(g) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policies LV6.13, LV7.4 and 7B of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Details of a scheme to provide a minimum of 20% of the parking spaces within the car parking areas outside of the adopted highway with active charging points for electric vehicles, with an additional 20% of spaces being provided with passive charging provision, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority within 6 months of the commencement of the superstructure works within Phase 1A and / or Phase 1B (as relevant).   The approved details shall be implemented prior to the first occupation of the relevant Phase of development.  Reason: In the interest of the environment and improving air quality in accordance with policies 6.13 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(e), 1.1(j), 1.1(k) and 1.2(k) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | The dedicated bicycle storage enclosures for the residential units and the seven spaces for visitors to the community centre / retail shop illustrated on the approved drawings shall be provided and ready for use prior to the first occupation of the residential units and / or community centre and / or retail shop and these facilities shall thereafter only be used for cycle storage.  Reason: To ensure adequate cycle parking is provided within the development in pursuance of the objectives of sustainability and encouraging the use of modes of transport other than private motor vehicles in accordance with policy 6.9 of the London Plan 2015, and policies 1.1(k) and 1.1(g) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012. | The dedicated refuse / recycling enclosures shown on the approved drawings shall be provided prior to the first occupation of any dwelling in the relevant core of the apartment building(s) and / or dwellinghouse to which the store serves.   Reason:  To secure the necessary recycling and waste enclosures to support the development and to ensure that responsible waste management practices are adhered to in the interests of the visual amenity of the area and in accordance with policy 5.17 of the London Plan 2015; policy 1.1(e) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and SPG 4: Refuse and Recycling Facilities. | Prior to the first occupation of the approved community centre and / or
